<subsection xml:id="subsec-equations-of-mirror-lines" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Equations of Mirror Lines</title>
    <objectives component="outcomes">
        <introduction xml:id="auto_uxja4g24">
            <dl>
                <li xml:id="auto_m9f1jnct">
                    <title>Strand</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_jho3w9uu">
                        2.0 Measurements and Geometry
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_wxlbz2m5">
                    <title>Sub-Strand</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_kge7w330">
                        2.2 Reflection and Congruence
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_a55d824c">
                    <title>Specific Learning Outcomes</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_9pqwh7ym">
                        Determine the equation of the mirror line given an object and its image
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_51j1ku0w" component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Grade Level</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_760yhggj">
                        10
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_23677t29" component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Estimated Duration</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_20lspvsj">
                        40 minutes
                    </p>
                </li>
            </dl>
            <p xml:id="auto_86siwp1u" component="lesson-plan">
                <p xml:id="auto_b9h5366i"> Upon completion of this lesson, learners will be able to:
                <ol>
                    <li xml:id="auto_2hnjeyht">
                        <p xml:id="auto_yexrct9p">
                            <alert>Know (Conceptual Understanding):</alert> Recall that the mirror line is the perpendicular bisector of the segment joining any point to its image. Understand that a line of reflection can be defined by an equation. Identify that the midpoint lies on the mirror line. State midpoint formula and gradient formula.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_24jeyxrx">
                        <p xml:id="auto_0a3s9o02">
                            <alert>Do (Procedural Skill):</alert> Determine the equation of the mirror line by finding the perpendicular bisector. Calculate midpoint. Calculate gradient using two known points. Apply point-slope form <m>y - y_1 = m(x - x_1)</m>. Verify with other points.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_ppzwbvcm">
                        <p xml:id="auto_v3qsqarp">
                            <alert>Apply (Application/Problem-Solving):</alert> Determine mirror line equations on the Cartesian plane. Recognise standard mirror lines (<m>x = 0</m>, <m>y = 0</m>, <m>y = x</m>, <m>y = -x</m>). Solve problems involving circles and other shapes.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
                </p>
            </p>
        </introduction>
        <ul>
            <li xml:id="auto_pi9iwwt0">Determine the equation of the mirror line given an object and its image</li>
        </ul>
    </objectives>
    <axiom component="resources">
        <!-- Link to blurb -->
        <xi:include href="../../resources-blurb-lesson.ptx" />

        <sbsgroup widths="45% 45%" margins="2% 2%">
            <sidebyside>
                <p xml:id="auto_u0t9ng1x">
                    <dataurl source="lesson_plans/measurements-and-geometry/reflection-and-congruence/equations-of-mirror-lines.pdf"> Lesson Plan </dataurl>
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_mmhpyxkt">
                    <dataurl source="lesson_plans/measurements-and-geometry/reflection-and-congruence/step-by-step-guide_equations-of-mirror-lines.pdf"> Step-by-Step Guide </dataurl>
                </p>
            </sidebyside>
        </sbsgroup>
    </axiom>
    <xi:include href="../../resources-materials.ptx" />

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Problem-Solving and Discovery</title>
        <dl>
            <li xml:id="auto_ut3ks2cw">
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_lg28da8y">
                    15 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_0phz0ism">
                <title>Objective</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_z7qc0bdx">
                    To discover the concept of the line of reflection through hands-on folding and observation on the Cartesian plane.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_d09r1n27">
                <title>Teacher's Role</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_9zmjm4h2">
                    The teacher circulates among groups, asking probing questions (e.g., <q>Where does the fold line appear?</q>, <q>Can you describe the fold line using the axes?</q>). The teacher guides learners to notice that the fold line bisects each connecting segment at right angles and to find the equation without folding.
                </p>
            </li>
        </dl>
    </axiom>

    <activity xml:id="auto_c0nvxcif">
      <p xml:id="auto_9myyj4rw">
        <term>Work in groups</term>
      </p>
      <p xml:id="auto_i8hga7kc">
        Determine the line of reflection that created the reflected image below.
      </p>

      <image>
        <shortdescription>Line of reflection</shortdescription>
        <latex-image label="Object_image">
          \begin{tikzpicture}
            
            % Draw the grid lines
            \draw[step=1,gray,very thin] (-5,-5) grid (5,5);

            % Draw the axes
            \draw[thin,-&gt;] (-5,0) -- (5,0) node[right] {x-axis};
            \foreach \x in {-4,...,4}{
            \draw(\x,.25)--(\x,-.25) node[below]{\x};
             }

            \draw[thin,-&gt;] (0,-5) -- (0,5) node[above] {y-axis}; 
            \foreach \y/\ytext in {-4/-4,-3/-3,-2/-2,-1/-1,0/0,1/1, 2/2, 3/3, 4/4}
            \draw[shift={(0,\y)}] (2pt,0pt) -- (-2pt,0pt) node[left] {$\ytext$};


            % Draw the original object
            \fill[blue,opacity=0.3] (-4,1) -- (-2,4) -- (-1,3) -- (-3,0) --cycle;
            \draw[blue,thick](-4,1) -- (-2,4) -- (-1,3) -- (-3,0) -- cycle;
            \node[blue] at (-4.2,1) {A};
            \node[above,blue] at (-2.2,4) {B};
            \node[right,blue] at (-1,3) {C};
            \node[left,blue] at (-2.5,0) {D};

            % Calculate and draw the image
            \fill[green,opacity=0.3] (4,1) -- (2,4) -- (1,3) --(3,0) -- cycle;
            \draw[green,thick] (4,1) -- (2,4) -- (1,3) --(3,0) -- cycle;
            \node[green] at (4.2,1) {A'};
            \node[above,green] at (2.2,4) {B'};
            \node[left,green] at (1,3){C'};
            \node[right,green] at (2.5,0) {D'};
          \end{tikzpicture}
        </latex-image>
      </image>

      <p xml:id="auto_a4bmher2">
         Copy the figure above on a graph paper
      </p>
      <p xml:id="auto_7l9keamo">
        Fold your graph paper such that the points of the objects match with their respective images.
         Where does the fold line appear? 
      </p>
    </activity>
    <insight xml:id="auto_rpmzhvgu">
      <p xml:id="auto_q2nzgk2d">
        <ul xml:id="auto_yj8p3p1a">
          <li xml:id="auto_h9aynxsn">
            <p xml:id="auto_sffflcp6">
              You notice that the fold line appears exactly on the y-axis. Therefore, the line of reflection is the y-axis.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li xml:id="auto_6knuq03v">
            <p xml:id="auto_scqtuou1">
              A line of reflection can be defined with an equation. From the activity, the equation of the line of reflection is <m>x = 0.</m>
            </p>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </p>
    </insight>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Structured Instruction</title>
        <p xml:id="auto_sorvawww">
            <dl>
            <li xml:id="auto_ea9mkxct">
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_q456xczv">
                    10 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_hc53xntk">
                <title>Objective</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_h6yos9e6">
                    To formalize the five-step method for determining the equation of a mirror line and recognise common mirror lines.
                </p>
            </li>
            </dl>
        </p>
        <paragraphs>
            <title>Key Takeaways</title>
            <ol>
                <li xml:id="auto_khetfaxk">
                    <p xml:id="auto_0b793c2r">
                        <alert>Five-Step Method:</alert> 1. Identify corresponding pairs of object and image points. 2. Check if any point maps to itself (the mirror line passes through it). 3. Find the midpoint of a pair. 4. Calculate the gradient of the segment joining the pair, then find the perpendicular gradient. 5. Write the equation using point-slope form.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_bzq7suz1">
                    <p xml:id="auto_7o5wqix5">
                        <alert>Common Mirror Lines:</alert> y-axis (<m>x = 0</m>): x-coordinates change sign, y stays the same. x-axis (<m>y = 0</m>): y-coordinates change sign, x stays the same. <m>y = x</m>: coordinates swap. <m>y = -x</m>: coordinates swap and change sign.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_ib0vik92">
                    <p xml:id="auto_cs03okpt">
                        <alert>Addressing Misconceptions:</alert> <q>The mirror line is NOT the line connecting the object to its image — it BISECTS that line at right angles.</q>
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </paragraphs>
    </axiom>

    <p xml:id="auto_tem9iw06">
        In the activity above, you determined the line of reflection by folding the graph paper.
        However, there are other methods to determine the line of reflection. In the next example, you will determine the line of reflection using algebraic methods.
    </p>
    <p xml:id="auto_uqh1vsjk">
        You will need to use the following properties of reflection:
        <ul>
        <li xml:id="auto_cbutm5to">
            The line of reflection is the perpendicular bisector of the line segment connecting a point and its image.
        </li>
        <li xml:id="auto_5qpcut2m">
            The distance from the object to the mirror line is the same as that of mirror line to the image.
        </li>
        </ul>
    </p>
    <p xml:id="auto_vtnoh08p">
        You will also need to use the following properties of lines:
        <ul>
        <li xml:id="auto_id8sqstf">
            The gradient of a line is the change in y-coordinates divided by the change in x-coordinates.
        </li>
        <li xml:id="auto_zdq7933e">
            The equation of a line can be expressed as <md>y - y_1 = m (x - x_1)</md> where <m>(x_1,y_1)</m> is a point on the line and <m>m</m> is the gradient of the line.
        </li>
        </ul>
    </p>

    <paragraphs>
        <title>Five-Step Method for Finding the Equation of a Mirror Line</title>
        <tabular bottom="medium" top="medium" left="medium" right="medium">
            <row header="yes">
                <cell>Step</cell>
                <cell>Action</cell>
            </row>
            <row>
                <cell>1</cell>
                <cell>Identify corresponding pairs of object and image points.</cell>
            </row>
            <row>
                <cell>2</cell>
                <cell>Check if any point maps to itself — the mirror line passes through it.</cell>
            </row>
            <row>
                <cell>3</cell>
                <cell>Find the midpoint of a pair using <m>\left(\frac{x_1+x_2}{2},\frac{y_1+y_2}{2}\right)</m>.</cell>
            </row>
            <row>
                <cell>4</cell>
                <cell>Calculate the gradient of the segment joining the pair, then find the perpendicular gradient (<m>m_\perp = -\frac{1}{m}</m>).</cell>
            </row>
            <row>
                <cell>5</cell>
                <cell>Write the equation using point-slope form: <m>y - y_1 = m(x - x_1)</m>.</cell>
            </row>
        </tabular>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs>
        <title>Common Mirror Lines</title>
        <tabular bottom="medium" top="medium" left="medium" right="medium">
            <row header="yes">
                <cell>Mirror Line</cell>
                <cell>Equation</cell>
                <cell>How to Recognise</cell>
            </row>
            <row>
                <cell>y-axis</cell>
                <cell><m>x = 0</m></cell>
                <cell>x-coordinates change sign, y stays the same</cell>
            </row>
            <row>
                <cell>x-axis</cell>
                <cell><m>y = 0</m></cell>
                <cell>y-coordinates change sign, x stays the same</cell>
            </row>
            <row>
                <cell>Line <m>y = x</m></cell>
                <cell><m>y = x</m></cell>
                <cell>Coordinates swap: <m>(a,b) \to (b,a)</m></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
                <cell>Line <m>y = -x</m></cell>
                <cell><m>y = -x</m></cell>
                <cell>Coordinates swap and change sign: <m>(a,b) \to (-b,-a)</m></cell>
            </row>
        </tabular>
    </paragraphs>

    <warning>
        <p xml:id="auto_br0red3o">
            The mirror line is <em>not</em> the line connecting the object to its image — it <em>bisects</em> that line at right angles.
        </p>
    </warning>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Practice and Application / Elaborate</title>
        <p xml:id="auto_eiygoout">
            <dl>
            <li xml:id="auto_03igt8rs">
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_8u4kmpep">
                    10 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_0do2nz5i">
                <title>Objective</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_kfapxx0r">
                    To apply the five-step method to determine equations of mirror lines in a variety of problems.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_ug6my8g6">
                <title>Teacher's Role</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_h48zmn8x">
                    The teacher emphasizes the five-step method and guides learners through worked examples, highlighting how to identify corresponding points, find midpoints, calculate gradients, and write equations.
                </p>
            </li>
            </dl>
        </p>
    </axiom>

    <example xml:id="auto_677go4pw">
      <statement>
        <p xml:id="auto_6n243pfq">
          Determine the equation of the line of reflection.
        </p>

        <image>
        <shortdescription>Line of reflection</shortdescription>
        <latex-image label="Object_image_example">
          \begin{tikzpicture}
            
            % Draw the grid lines
            \draw[step=1,gray,very thin] (-5,-5) grid (5,5);

            % Draw the axes
            \draw[thin,-&gt;] (-5,0) -- (5,0) node[right] {x-axis};
            \foreach \x in {-4,...,4}{
            \draw(\x,.25)--(\x,-.25) node[below]{\x};
             }

            \draw[thin,-&gt;] (0,-5) -- (0,5) node[above] {y-axis}; 
            \foreach \y/\ytext in {-4/-4,-3/-3,-2/-2,-1/-1,0/0,1/1, 2/2, 3/3, 4/4}
            \draw[shift={(0,\y)}] (2pt,0pt) -- (-2pt,0pt) node[left] {$\ytext$};


            % Draw the original object
            \fill[blue,opacity=0.3] (2,5) -- (2,3) -- (4,2) -- (0,0) --cycle;
            \draw[blue,thick] (2,5) -- (2,3) -- (4,2) -- (0,0) -- cycle;
            \node[blue] at (2.2,5.2) {A};
            \node[blue] at (2.2,3) {B};
            \node[blue] at (4.2,2) {C};
            \node[left,blue] at (.1,.2) {D};
            

            % Calculate and draw the image
            \fill[red,opacity=0.3](-5,-2) -- (-3,-2) -- (-2,-4) -- (0,0) -- cycle;
            \draw[red,thick] (-5,-2) -- (-3,-2) -- (-2,-4) -- (0,0) -- cycle;
            \node[red] at (-5.2,-2) {A'};
            \node[below,red] at (-3.2,-2) {B'};
            \node[red] at (-2.2,-4){C'};
            \node[right,red] at (-.1,-.1) {D'};
            
          \end{tikzpicture}
        </latex-image>
      </image>

      </statement>

      <solution>
        <p xml:id="auto_mvq5r772">
          The coordinates of <m>D \text{ and } D'</m> are at <m>(0,0),</m> tells you that the line of reflection passes through <m>(0,0).</m>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_s08au99x">
          Connect point <m>C \text{ to } C'</m> with a line. The line of reflection is the perpendicular bisector of <m>C \text{ and } C'.</m>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_d3mhgy8m">
          From the properties of reflection, the distance from the object to the mirror line is the same as that of mirror line to the image.
           Therefore, the line of reflection passes through the midpoint of the line connecting <m>C \text{ to } C'.</m>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_da1u3v20">
          Coordinates for <m>C \text{ is }(4,2)</m> and that of <m>C' \text{ is } (-2,-4).</m>
          The mid point of line <m>CC'</m> is: 
          <me>\left(    \frac{4 + -2}{2},\frac{2 + -4}{2}   \right) = (1,-1)</me>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_34dizuz6">
          Since you know that the line of reflection passes through <m>(0,0) \text{ and } (1,-1),</m> the gradient of the reflection line is:
          <me>m = \frac{-1 - 0}{1 - 0} = -1</me>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_e5ddgkkz">
          Therefore taking points <m>(x,y) \text { and } (1,-1),</m> the equation of the line of reflection is :
          <me>y - y_1 = m (x - x_1)</me>
          <me>y - -1 = -1 (x - 1)</me>
          <me>y + 1 = -x + 1</me>
          <me>y = -x</me>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <exploration xml:id="auto_6gg4k15v">
        <title>Changing Equations of Mirror Lines</title>
    <p xml:id="auto_fah6wnm9">
        Manipulate the equation of the mirror line in the interactive below! Can you put in the answer from <xref ref="auto_677go4pw"/> and see if the image matches the one in the example?
    </p>
    <figure xml:id="fig-equation-mirror-line">
    <caption>
        An interactive demonstration of reflection across a mirror line.
    </caption>

        <interactive xml:id="interactive-equation-mirror-line" 
                    platform="jsxgraph" 
                    width="90%" 
                    aspect="1:1" 
                    source="jsxgraph/equation-mirror-line.js">
            <slate xml:id="jsxgraph-equation-mirror-line" 
                surface="jsxboard" 
                aspect="1:1"/>
            <instructions>
            <p xml:id="auto_1e2jipeo">Enter different values for the slope (<m>m</m>) and y-intercept (<m>c</m>) in the input fields to see how the mirror line and reflected image change. You can use this to check your answer to <xref ref="auto_677go4pw"/>. You can also move around the blue polygon<mdash/>this could help for other exercises!</p>
            </instructions>
        </interactive>

    </figure>
            
    </exploration>

    <example xml:id="auto_job2no36">
      <statement>
        <p xml:id="auto_0s8vypep">
          From the figure below, determine the equation of the line of reflection.
        </p>
        <image>
          <shortdescription></shortdescription>
          <latex-image label="overlap_square">
             \begin{tikzpicture}
                % Draw the grid lines
                \draw[step=1,gray,very thin] (-5,-5) grid (5,5);

                 % Draw the axes
                \draw[thin,-&gt;] (-5,0) -- (5,0) node[right] {x-axis};
                \foreach \x in {-4,...,4}{
                \draw(\x,.25)--(\x,-.25) node[below]{\x};
                }
              
                \draw[thin,-&gt;] (0,-5) -- (0,5) node[above] {y-axis}; 
                \foreach \y/\ytext in {-4/-4,-3/-3,-2/-2,-1/-1,0/0,1/1,2/2,3/3,4/4}
                \draw[shift={(0,\y)}] (2pt,0pt) -- (-2pt,0pt) node[left] {$\ytext$};

                % Define original square nodes
                \coordinate (A) at (1,1);
                \coordinate (B) at (3,1);
                \coordinate (C) at (3,3);
                \coordinate (D) at (1,3);

                % Draw the original square using nodes
                \fill[blue,opacity=0.3] (A) -- (B) -- (C) -- (D) -- cycle;
                \draw[blue,thick] (A) -- (B) -- (C) -- (D) -- cycle;

                % Label original nodes (positioned relative to nodes)
                \node[blue,below left] at (A) {A};
                \node[blue,below right] at (B) {B};
                \node[blue,above right] at (C) {C};
                \node[blue,above left] at (D) {D};

                % Define image square nodes (updated positions)
                \coordinate (Aprime) at (4,4);
                \coordinate (Bprime) at (4,2);
                \coordinate (Cprime) at (2,2);
                \coordinate (Dprime) at (2,4);

                % Draw the image square using nodes
                \fill[red,opacity=0.3] (Aprime) -- (Bprime) -- (Cprime) -- (Dprime) -- cycle;
                \draw[red,thick] (Aprime) -- (Bprime) -- (Cprime) -- (Dprime) -- cycle;

                % Label image nodes (positioned relative to nodes)
                \node[red,above right] at (Aprime) {A'};
                \node[red,below right] at (Bprime) {B'};
                \node[red,below left] at (Cprime) {C'};
                \node[red,above left] at (Dprime) {D'};
              \end{tikzpicture}
          </latex-image>
        </image>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p xml:id="auto_iw9wf6co">
          The coordinates of <m>A \text{ and } A'</m> are <m>(1,1) \text{ and } (4,4),</m> so the line of reflection is the perpendicular bisector of the segment joining these points.
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_6r9rn8ta">
          The midpoint of <m>AA'</m> is:
          <me>\left( \frac{1 + 4}{2},\frac{1 + 4}{2} \right) = (2.5,2.5)</me>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_s64sri22">
          The gradient of the segment <m>AA'</m> is <me>m_{AA'} = \frac{4 - 1}{4 - 1} = 1.</me>
          The line of reflection is perpendicular to this segment, so its gradient is <me>m = -1.</me>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_cc79n3wj">
          Using point <m>(2.5,2.5)</m> and slope <m>-1</m>, the equation is:
          <me>y - 2.5 = -1(x - 2.5)</me>
          <me>y - 2.5 = -x + 2.5</me>
          <me>y = -x + 5</me>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>

